Task 2: Inline, Internal, and External CSS

Differences:
- Inline: Styles are applied directly to HTML elements using the style attribute.
- Internal: Styles are defined within the <head> section of the HTML document using <style> tags.
- External: Styles are defined in a separate CSS file linked to the HTML document using the <link> tag.
Example:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>CSS Styles</title>
    <style>
        /* Internal CSS */
        h1 {
            color: red;
        }
    </style>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css"> </head>
<body>
    <h1 style="color: blue;">Inline CSS</h1>
    <h1>Internal CSS</h1>
    <p>Text with external CSS</p>
</body>
</html>

Advantages and Disadvantages:
- Inline: Easy to apply styles to individual elements, but can clutter HTML code.
- Internal: Centralizes styles within the HTML document, but can make maintenance difficult for large projects.
- External: Separates structure from presentation, improves readability, and facilitates code reuse.
